objects.name: NETWIRE
objects.description:
[NETWIRE](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0198) is a publicly available, multiplatform remote administration tool (RAT) that has been widely used by criminal and APT groups since at least 2012.

It is used by the threat actors to steal victim's passwords, login credentials and credit card data. NETWIRE has the capability to remotely execute the commands and collects filesystem information.

The almost-commoditized RAT is sold in underground forums for between $40 and $140 dollars. 

![](https://app.sekoia.io/api/v2/inthreat/images/61a6027ee7f9afbd13acfad994c0bd809d235c214ca832c05763fa739665f0e3.png)
                               Examples of publications about Netwire on several hacking forums

objects.name: NanoCore
objects.description:
[NanoCore](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0336) is a modular remote access tool developed in .NET that can be used to spy on victims and steal information. It has been used by threat actors since 2013.

After 2017, there are leaked versions of Nanocore that are widely used by the threat actors in their campaigns.

According to Talos, starting with October 2021, threat actors were using Nanocore in its 1.2.2.0 version which is a leaked version with an Oct. 26, 2021 build date.

objects.name: MWDB
objects.description:
The MWDB system (also known as the Malware Database) is a repository for storing malware samples and information acquired during their analysis. The simplest example of this type of data can be the relation of a specific sample with a given malware family, or the addresses of the C&C servers used by it.

Indicators from known malware are automatically imported in Intelligence Center by playbook.

objects.description:
[Remcos](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0332) is a closed-source tool that is marketed as a remote control and surveillance software by a company called Breaking Security.
